crops.origin: Santarem area, on the Tapajos, Para, Brazil (found along a roadside about 6 miles from Santarem)
crops.presented_by: Mr. Walter Fischer, Campo de Cultura Experimental Paraense
crops.institution_involved: Campo de Cultura Experimental Paraense, Para, Brazil
crops.description: A species of Sapindus found along a roadside about 6 miles from Santarem. The tree grows to a height of 30 to 40 feet and is found along the borders of clearings. Natives were familiar with the saponifying property of the seeds but, as far as the presenter could learn, made no use of them. Santarem is located north of the Tapajos on the Amazon, about 500 miles from Para. Presented by Mr. Walter Fischer, Campo de Cultura Experimental Paraense, Para, Brazil.

crops.origin: Barbados (collected in Barbados); distribution noted in sandy soil in southern Florida, the West Indies, and tropical South America
crops.presented_by: Mr. Walter Fischer, Campo de Cultura Experimental Paraense
crops.institution_involved: Campo de Cultura Experimental Paraense, Para, Brazil
crops.description: One of two varieties of seeds found and collected in Barbados. Local name is 'bread and cheese.' Seeds are from an attractive ornamental small tree much used as a border shrub and as a hedge plant; foliage is clean and compound, each leaf with a twin pair of obovate leaflets. The plant bears dense panicles of pods which open and twist when ripe, showing shiny-black small seeds each with an attached aril. This hedge plant would be well adapted to southern Florida and may already exist there. Note for this lot: "Seed with white aril." Distribution: sandy soil in southern Florida, the West Indies, and the tropical part of South America. Presented by Mr. Walter Fischer.
